and I have the pleasure of being at Cala Vista and talking to Les Appelt,
one of the most generous, thoughtful Aggies of all time.
Les, why did you attend A&M in the first place?
My brother had attended A&M, a very devoted Aggie.
He was several years ahead of me, and the other was probably largely economic.
It was probably the least costly major college to attend.
My economics in my first two years at A&M were covered by the savings I had,

Now you entered as a freshman in the fall of, fall of 36.
You had visited the campus a number of times before enrolling.
When you went to enroll, how did you get there?
No, I left my folks in the back seat.
Yeah, now what were the, what did you take with you, in terms of clothing and supplies?
You see at that time, uniforms were, it was so inconsequential that I don't remember what it is.
Describe if you can how you were received.
How did you get in a dormitory, get in a unit, get enrolled?
I remember not really too good on that, except that,
the dormitory assignment had been made, and I knew where to go by the sophomores.
The leader began giving us instructions in campusology, and we'd do anything right.
The fact that I had this job at MSL caused some confusion among our sophomores.
We were, luckily, we were in a hall dormitory, which was fortunate for me to just directly cross the street of those recent halls.
The fact that I had to go to MSL exempted me from marching in with the outfit, which annoyed the sophomores going in.
So, it turned out that about once a month, they would have a special session.
At that time, it would come to known as ass tears.
My transgressions didn't, so we were fortunate enough to have a job at MSL,
to show you how far the university progressed, where it reserved for football.
We had John Kimbrough, Ralph, and all the freshmen back then, all the football players.
I think they stayed in there, my freshman, sophomore year, as soon as we could now have.
Can you describe a typical dormitory room at that time?
What did y'all have in it?
Well, typical there was, there'd be two rooms, so it was just basically a shop.
The floors were plastered and painted.
The size of the room, I'd say, there was room for rainbows.
I'd say we could have two desks.
I'd say the room was about to have ten, about twelve.
We brought in anything like that.
We got to do that ourselves.
Usually, we had to, somehow or another, we always had to throw up something.
So, we'd hit the deck with more beds.
We wouldn't be in that cold floor.
Describe the campus physically when you arrived.
There was quite a bit of space between what was the main door.
Between the library and that main building.
Across the street from us, now the ladies' dormitory.
The building that was used in the Amble Hill group department.
And they stored hay in it.
And they had mangers there where they feed the animals.
